                \n {"practice":"6","code":"DM-4","subCode":"4) disabling or removing features;","explanation":"The process involves identifying and mitigating security risks by disabling or removing non-essential features that could introduce vulnerabilities in industrial control systems (ICS).","context":"In ICS environments, unnecessary features can increase attack surfaces. Disabling or removing them reduces potential entry points for attackers while maintaining operational integrity.","challenges":["Identifying non-critical features without impacting core functionality. Example: A legacy SCADA system may rely on deprecated protocols that cannot be easily removed.","Assessing the security impact of each feature. Example: A web interface in a PLC may be convenient but poses significant risks if not properly secured.","Managing stakeholder resistance to feature removal. Example: Operators may oppose disabling remote access due to convenience, despite security risks.","Ensuring compatibility with existing systems post-removal. Example: Disabling a legacy protocol may break communication with older devices.","Documenting changes for audit and compliance. Example: Failing to record disabled features may lead to non-compliance with IEC 62443-4-1."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Conduct a thorough risk assessment before disabling features. Example: Evaluate whether a web server in an RTU is necessary for operations or can be disabled. Link: Siemens guide on secure RTU configurations.","url":" https://new.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-software/automation-software/tia-portal.html","url_description":"Siemens' guide on secure configurations for RTUs, relevant to DM-4 subCode 4."},{"description":"Implement change management procedures for feature removal. Example: Use a ticketing system to track and approve feature disablement in ICS devices. Link: Rockwell Automation's change management whitepaper.","url":"https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/ca